indya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arches","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, English: locative name from any of various places in France called Arques (Eure, Pas-de-Calais, Seine-Maritime). The name was sometimes reduced to   Arch  .","2  English: variant of   Arch   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Arch","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone living by a bridge, from Middle English, Old French <i>arche</i> ‘arch’ (i.e. of a bridge).","English (of Norman origin): shortened form of <b>Arches</b>, a habitational name from any of various places in France called Arques (Eure, Pas-de-Calais, Seine-Maritime).","Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Arh</b>: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Areh</i>, an old vernacular form of <i>Henrik</i> (see   Henry   1)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":17,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":26,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":61,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":92,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":117,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Arches was born in 1198, in Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Sir William de Arches, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. William de Arches, was 28. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Robert de Arches."},"et":{"1198–":"1198–Surnud","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1202–Female":"1202–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1227–1273":"1227–1273","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1190":"1190","1198":"1198","1273":"1273","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1228":"umbes 1228","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1166":"1166","1317":"1317","Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wrawby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1198–":"1198–Kuollut","1198–Male":"1198–Kuollut","1202–Female":"1202–Kuollut","1228–Female":"1228–Kuollut","1227–1273":"1227–1273","1166–Male":"1166–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1198":"1198","1273":"1273","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1228":"noin 1228","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1166":"1166","1317":"1317","Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wrawby, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1198–":"1198–Décédé","1198–Male":"1198–Décédé","1202–Female":"1202–Décédée","1228–Female":"1228–Décédée","1227–1273":"1227–1273","1166–Male":"1166–Décédé","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1190":"1190","1198":"1198","1273":"1273","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1315":"1315","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1228":"environ 1228","1224":"1224","1202":"1202","1166":"1166","1317":"1317","Wrawby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wrawby, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert de Arches est né en